    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i see. but if the original meaning of the text is so important, how do they handle things like modern technology or privacy rights that the founders couldn't have possibly imagined? doesn't that make the whole 'original meaning' thing feel a bit outdated or even impractical for a modern society?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalists address the issue of unanticipated modern developments, like technology and privacy rights, by sticking to the principles and values that are inherently present in the Constitution, even if the specific applications were not foreseen. For example, they might look at the Fourth Amendment's protection against unreasonable searches and seizures and apply those fundamental principles to contemporary issues like digital privacy, despite the technology being nonexistent at the time.\n\nFurthermore, originalists argue that the Constitution's enduring principles are broad enough to encompass a range of unforeseen circumstances, and that the Founding Fathers' work was not meant to be a rigid set of instructions. Instead, it was intended to establish a framework for government that could adapt to new challenges while preserving basic liberties. They assert that while the specific applications of the Constitution may change over time, the core values and framework remain relevant and capable of addressing modern issues within the bounds of the original understanding.",
      "source": "target",
